    "overview": "<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Transform your webcam and monitor into a desktop <strong>hologram</strong>!</p><p style=\"text-align: center;\">SHolo maps eye position to a virtual space and uses hand gestures to impart angular velocity or stop motion, producing a Tony Stark–style floating-object interaction on a normal screen.</p>",
    "content": "<h2>The Vision</h2><p>There’s a <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" class=\"text-blue-600 underline hover:text-blue-800\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ddk9ci6geSs\">scene</a> I love in <strong>Iron-Man 2</strong>: Tony Stark standing in front of floating holograms, manipulating them with a casual swipe of his hand.<br>It’s cinematic, but it’s also the perfect metaphor for <strong>human-computer interaction</strong>: intuitive, responsive, alive.</p><p>I wanted to recreate that feeling on a regular desktop. <strong>No special hardware</strong>, just a monitor and a webcam.<br>And that’s how <strong>SHolo</strong> (<strong>S</strong>creen <strong>Holo</strong>gram) was born.</p><h2>The Concept</h2><p>Before writing a single line of code, I started by answering something simple: <strong>how do we perceive depth?</strong></p><p>And so I played around with real-world objects: moving them, keeping my eyes still, rolling my eyes, … and I found something very simple but powerful (I could have just Googled it, but it wouldn't have been as fun):</p><blockquote><p><strong>Manuel</strong>(*)<strong>'s Theorem</strong></p><p>- When you move only your eyes, the world stays still.</p><p>- When you move your head, everything shifts: that's what gives us the true sense of three-dimensionality.</p><p>(*) I am Manuel</p></blockquote><p>That’s when I realized: it’s not <em>how</em> the eyes move that matters, but <em>where</em> they are.</p><p>So, like any engineer trying to simplify a complex system, I reduced the problem to its essence: <strong>tracking only the pupils’ position</strong> through a webcam.</p><p>By capturing the eyes’ relative position and estimating their distance from the camera (through interpupillary distance mapped to pixel distance and the camera’s focal length) I could reconstruct a virtual version of my viewpoint inside the software!</p><gitcms-media data-path=\"media/idea-1761865177239.jpg\" data-filename=\"idea-1761865177239.jpg\" data-thumbnail=\"data:application/vnd.github.raw;base64,\" alt=\"idea-1761865177239.jpg\" title=\"idea-1761865177239.jpg\"></gitcms-media><p>From there, it was just a matter of connecting that virtual “camera” to the 3D rendering engine.</p><p>And as for the hand gestures, well, I had a feeling I could come up with something.</p><p>So… that was all! <strong>No special hardware</strong>: exactly what I wanted.<br>Just a webcam, a monitor, and a bit of math.</p><p>With that realization, I jumped straight into coding: first building the 3D renderer, then integrating eye-tracking for camera control, then hand-tracking for interaction and finally merging everything into a single, living system.</p><h1>How It Works</h1><p>At its core, SHolo is an experimental <strong>Python application</strong> that brings together <strong>MediaPipe</strong>, <strong>OpenCV</strong>, <strong>Trimesh</strong>, and <strong>Pyglet</strong> into a multi-threaded 3D environment.</p><h2>Core pipeline</h2><ol><li><p><strong>Eye tracking</strong>: MediaPipe Face Mesh locates eyes, estimates inter-pupillary distance (IPD), and maps gaze offset to yaw/pitch camera rotation.</p></li><li><p><strong>Hand tracking</strong>: MediaPipe Hands detects swipes and open-palm gestures to control motion.</p></li><li><p><strong>3D rendering</strong>: the scene is rendered in Trimesh via Pyglet, with live transformations driven by the detected inputs.</p></li><li><p><strong>Thread orchestration</strong>: The OpenCV detection loop runs independently from the Pyglet viewer to maintain responsiveness and avoid frame drops.</p></li></ol><p>The result: a seamless interaction where your eyes control <em>view</em>, and your hands control <em>motion</em>.</p><p>The modules are <code>eyes_tracking.py</code>, <code>hands_tracking.py</code>, and <code>view_3d.py</code>, orchestrated by <code>SHolo.py</code>.<br>Everything is modular, threaded, and tunable via <code>config.py</code>.</p><h2>Reflections + What Comes Next</h2><p>Building <strong>SHolo</strong> meant bridging two separate worlds: computer vision and 3D rendering, and making them connect in real time.</p><p>Mapping 2D landmarks into 3D transforms demanded careful calibration of depth and small-angle approximations.<br>Gesture recognition had to feel human and smooth, so I built in cooldowns, thresholds, and easing curves to simulate inertia.<br>Running both the tracking and the rendering loops in parallel threads pushed me to think like both a scientist and an artist, shaping a system that feels responsive, alive, and just a little bit magical.</p><p>But beyond the code, <strong>SHolo</strong> became something more than a technical demo.<br>It’s proof that immersive interaction doesn’t always require futuristic hardware. Sometimes, all it takes is curiosity, data, and imagination.<br>A webcam, a screen, and a few equations can already blur the line between digital and physical space.</p><p>And this is just the beginning! With further development, <strong>SHolo</strong> could evolve into:</p><ul><li><p>a virtual control interface for <strong>3D modeling</strong> and <strong>scientific visualization</strong>, where you manipulate complex data as if it floated before you;</p></li><li><p>an <strong>immersive gaming tool</strong> that lets players interact naturally with virtual environments, delivering VR-like experiences without the need for a dedicated headset.</p></li></ul><p><strong>SHolo</strong> started as a “what if…”<br>It’s for me a reminder that <strong>curiosity</strong>, when paired with the <strong>desire to experiment</strong>, can give life to something innovative and beautiful.</p>",
